# CRITICAL: PowerShell Only ‚Äî No Linux Commands

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

This rule has no exceptions. There is no scenario ‚Äî not familiarity with
bash, not a "probably works" guess, not a complex command ‚Äî that permits
using bash syntax in this project.

Prohibited judgement calls:
- "I'll use `&&` ‚Äî it might work." ‚Äî No. Use `;`. Always.
- "I'll use `cat <<'EOF'` for a multiline string." ‚Äî No. This is bash heredoc syntax. It does not exist in PowerShell.
- "I'll use `export VAR=value`." ‚Äî No. Use `$env:VAR = "value"`.
- "I'll use `.venv/bin/python`." ‚Äî No. Use `.venv\Scripts\python`.
- "I'll use `make lint`." ‚Äî No. Use `./make.ps1 lint`.

Before issuing any terminal command, mentally verify every token is
valid PowerShell. If unsure about a construct, look it up or ask ‚Äî do
not guess and submit.

---

**This machine runs Windows. There is no Linux shell, no bash, no WSL. Using bash syntax will cause commands to fail.**

This project runs on Windows. All terminal commands must use PowerShell syntax.

## Critical differences

| Task | PowerShell (correct) | Bash (never use) |
|---|---|---|
| Chain commands | `cmd1; cmd2` | `cmd1 && cmd2` |
| Set env var | `$env:VAR = "value"` | `export VAR=value` |
| Path separator | `\` or `/` (both work) | `/` only |
| List files | `ls` or `dir` | `ls` |
| Read file | `Get-Content file.txt` | `cat file.txt` |
| Delete file | `Remove-Item file.txt` | `rm file.txt` |
| Copy file | `Copy-Item src dst` | `cp src dst` |
| Move file | `Move-Item src dst` | `mv src dst` |
| Make directory | `New-Item -ItemType Directory dir` or `mkdir dir` | `mkdir dir` |

## Rules ‚Äî violation of any of these will break the command

- **NEVER use `&&`** to chain commands ‚Äî use `;` in PowerShell.
- **NEVER use `export`** to set environment variables ‚Äî use `$env:VAR = "value"`.
- **NEVER assume a Unix shell** ‚Äî no bash, no sh, no zsh.
- **NEVER use `.venv/bin/`** ‚Äî always use `.venv\Scripts\` for virtual environment binaries.
- **NEVER use `make`** ‚Äî always use `./make.ps1 <target>`.
- **ALWAYS use `;`** to separate multiple commands in a single shell call.

## Examples

```powershell
cd c:\Projects\prhrt\irs-data; .venv\Scripts\pytest.exe tests/ -v

$env:LOG_LEVEL = "DEBUG"; .venv\Scripts\python.exe -m irs_data

./make.ps1 lint
./make.ps1 test
```

## Multiline git commit messages

Heredocs (`<<'EOF'`) do not exist in PowerShell. Use a variable instead:

```powershell
$msg = "Short summary line`n`n- Detail one`n- Detail two`n- Detail three"
git commit -m $msg
```
